<div class="markdown prose w-full break-words dark:prose-invert dark"><p data-start="0" data-end="175" class="">The term <strong data-start="9" data-end="27">"context-free"</strong> in <strong data-start="31" data-end="62">Context-Free Language (CFL)</strong> comes from the <strong data-start="78" data-end="115">way its grammar rules are applied</strong>, not how it is processed by a <strong data-start="146" data-end="174">pushdown automaton (PDA)</strong>.</p>
<hr data-start="177" data-end="180" class="" style="">
<h3 data-start="182" data-end="220" class=""><strong data-start="186" data-end="220">Why is it called Context-Free?</strong></h3>
<p data-start="221" data-end="353" class="">A <strong data-start="223" data-end="253">Context-Free Grammar (CFG)</strong> is called <strong data-start="264" data-end="280">context-free</strong> because <strong data-start="289" data-end="340">production rules apply independently of context</strong>. That means:</p>
<ul data-start="355" data-end="576">
<li data-start="355" data-end="479" class="" style="">
<p data-start="357" data-end="479" class="">If a rule says <strong data-start="372" data-end="394"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi><mo>â†’</mo><mi>Î±</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">A \to \alpha</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.6833em;"></span><span class="mord mathnormal">A</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.2778em;"></span><span class="mrel">â†’</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.2778em;"></span></span><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.4306em;"></span><span class="mord mathnormal" style="margin-right: 0.0037em;">Î±</span></span></span></span></strong>, it can be applied <strong data-start="414" data-end="440">anywhere in the string</strong>, regardless of what surrounds <span class="katex"><span class="katex-m><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.6833em;"></span><span class="mord mathnormal">A</span></span></span></span>.</p>
</li>
<li data-start="480" data-end="576" class="" style="">
<p data-start="482" data-end="576" class="">This contrasts with <strong data-start="502" data-end="532">context-sensitive grammars</strong>, where rules depend on neighboring symbols.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<p data-start="578" data-end="602" class="">For example, in the CFG:</p>
<span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><semantics><mrow><mi>S</mi><mo>â†’</mo><mi>a</mi><mi>S</mi><mi>b</mi><mspace width="1em"></mspace><mi mathvariant="normal">âˆ£</mi><mspace width="1em"></mspace><mi>Ïµ</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="applon/x-tex">S \to aSb \quad | \quad \epsilon</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.6833em;"></span><span class="mord mathnormal" style="margin-right: 0.05764em;">S</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.2778em;"></span><span class="mrel">â†’</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.2778em;"></span></span><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 1em; vertical-align: -0.25em;"></span><span class="mord mathnormal">a</span><span class="mord mathnormal" style="margin-right: 0.05764em;">S</span><span class="mord mathnormal">b</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 1em;"></span><span class="mord">âˆ£</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 1em;"></span><span class="mord mathnormal">Ïµ</span></span></span></span></span>
<p data-start="642" data-end="757" class="">The rule <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><sema><mrow><mi>S</mi><mo>â†’</mo><mi>a</mi><mi>S</mi><mi>b</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">S \to aSb</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.6833em;"></span><span class="mord mathnormal" style="margin-right: 0.05764em;">S</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.2778em;"></span><span class="mrel">â†’</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.2778em;"></span></span><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.6944em;"></span><span class="mord mathnormal">a</span><span class="mord mathnormal" style="margin-right: 0.05764em;">S</span><span class="mord mathnormal">b</span></span></span></span> can be applied <strong data-start="682" data-end="694">whenever</strong> there is an <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>S</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">S</annotation></semantics></m</span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.6833em;"></span><span class="mord mathnormal" style="margin-right: 0.05764em;">S</span></span></span></span>, regardless of the surrounding characters.</p>
<hr data-start="759" data-end="762" class="" style="">
<h3 data-start="764" data-end="815" class=""><strong data-start="768" data-end="815">Doesn't the Stack in a PDA Provide Context?</strong></h3>
<p data-start="816" data-end="976" class="">A <strong data-start="818" data-end="846">Pushdown Automaton (PDA)</strong> uses a <strong data-start="854" data-end="863">stack</strong>, which stores information about previously read symbols, but this <strong data-start="930" data-end="967">does not violate context-freeness</strong> because:</p>
<ul data-start="978" data-end="1207">
<li data-start="978" data-end="1073" class="" style="">
<p data-start="980" data-end="1073" class="">The stack is used <strong data-start="998" data-end="1032">only to help process the input</strong>, not to determine <strong data-start="1051" data-end="1072">which rules apply</strong>.</p>
</li>
<li data-start="1074" data-end="1207" class="" style="">
<p data-start="1076" data-end="1207" class="">The PDA <strong data-start="1084" data-end="1148">still applies rules based solely on the current non-terminal</strong>, without considering surrounding characters in the string.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<p data-start="1209" data-end="1275" class="">In contrast, a <strong data-start="1224" data-end="1259">context-sensitive grammar (CSG)</strong> has rules like:</p>
<span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><semantics><mrow><mi>a</mi><mi>X</mi><mi>b</mi><mo>â†’</mo><mi>a</mi><mi>y</mi><mi>b</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">aXb \to ayb</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.6944em;"></span><sn class="mord mathnormal">a</span><span class="mord mathnormal" style="margin-right: 0.07847em;">X</span><span class="mord mathnormal">b</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.2778em;"></span><span class="mrel">â†’</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.2778em;"></span></span><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.8889em; vertical-align: -0.1944em;"></span><span class="mord mathnormal">a</span><span class="mord mathnormal" style="margin-right: 0.03588em;">y</span><span class="mord mathnormal">b</span></span></span></span></span>
<p data-start="1294" data-end="1458" class="">Here, <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.6833em;"></span><span class="mord mathnormal" style="margin-right: 0.07847em;">X</span>span></span></span> can only be replaced by <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>y</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">y</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.625em; vertical-align: -0.1944em;"></span><span class="mord mathnormal" style="margin-right: 0.03588em;">y</span></span></span></span> <strong data-start="1340" data-end="1382">when surrounded by <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>a</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">a</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.4306em;"></span><span class="mord mathnormal">a</span></span></span></span> and <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>b</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">b</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.6944em;"></span><span class="mord mathnormal">b</span></span></span></span></strong>. This dependency on the surrounding symbols makes it <strong data-start="1436" data-end="1457">context-sensitive</strong>.</p>
<hr data-start="1460" data-end="1463" class="" style="">
<h3 data-start="1465" data-end="1486" class=""><strong data-start="1469" data-end="1486">Key Takeaways</strong></h3>
<ul data-start="1487" data-end="1795">
<li data-start="1487" data-end="1560" class="" style="">
<p data-start="1489" data-end="1560" class=""><strong data-start="1489" data-end="1531">"Context-free" refers to grammar rules</strong>, not how they are processed.</p>
</li>
<li data-start="1561" data-end="1624" class="" style="">
<p data-start="1563" data-end="1624" class=""><strong data-start="1563" data-end="1623">A CFG applies rules independently of surrounding symbols</strong>.</p>
</li>
<li data-start="1625" data-end="1701" class="" style="">
<p data-start="1627" data-end="1701" class=""><strong data-start="1627" data-end="1700">A PDA uses a stack, but it doesnâ€™t make the grammar context-sensitive</strong>.</p>
</li>
<li data-start="1702" data-end="1795" class="" style="">
<p data-start="1704" data-end="1795" class=""><strong data-start="1704" data-end="1794">Context-sensitive languages require surrounding symbols to determine rule applications</strong>.</p>
</li>
</ul>
